abstract: These two progressives are in a bold — but awfully risky — place.

lead_paragraph: I’m no good at sartorial stuff, so I can’t describe how Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren were actually dressed. But I can tell you what they were effectively wearing: targets.

abstract: In an extended interview, the California senator explains why she thinks litmus-test questions aren’t helpful and how she is approaching this campaign.
snippet: In an extended interview, the California senator explains why she thinks litmus-test questions aren’t helpful and how she is approaching this campaign.
lead_paragraph: Senator Kamala Harris has emerged as one of the most important candidates in the Democratic primary, besting Joseph R. Biden Jr. in a debate last month and exciting liberal voters who see her as a strong challenger to President Trump. But Ms. Harris has eluded ideological definition for much of the race.

abstract: “I felt like at any moment they were about to go, ‘By the way, Elizabeth, did you notice that Klobuchar totally stole your look?’” Trevor Noah joked Tuesday.

abstract: Invoking family stories of coming to America, many left-leaning voters in the multiethnic city of Racine say immigrants should enter legally.
snippet: Invoking family stories of coming to America, many left-leaning voters in the multiethnic city of Racine say immigrants should enter legally.
lead_paragraph: RACINE, Wis. — In this old manufacturing city that supported Hillary Clinton in 2016, dislike for President Trump runs wide and deep. Images of crying children at the Mexican border typically serve as Exhibit A on the list of grievances that Democratic voters cite against the president.

headline_main: Boris Johnson, Democratic Party, North Korea: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: The candidates sparred angrily over whether to wipe out private health insurance and institute a government-run health system.
snippet: The candidates sparred angrily over whether to wipe out private health insurance and institute a government-run health system.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It took only one question — the very first — in Tuesday night’s Democratic presidential primary debate to make it clear that the issue that united the party in last year’s congressional elections in many ways now divides it.

abstract: The 77-year-old democratic socialist from Vermont made clear that he could still own the Democratic debate. And the debate stage.
snippet: The 77-year-old democratic socialist from Vermont made clear that he could still own the Democratic debate. And the debate stage.
lead_paragraph: Bernie Sanders was at it again — center stage, his baritone building to something — right hand raised and restless, as if he were scribbling his words on an invisible chalkboard.
